WEBVTT

00:00:08.583 --> 00:00:09.416
Professor: So you guys are

00:00:09.416 --> 00:00:12.416
saying that the circuit just caught on
fire by itself?

00:00:12.500 --> 00:00:13.208
Okay.

00:00:13.208 --> 00:00:15.916
Seems like
the memory chip is still intact.

00:00:15.916 --> 00:00:17.166
Let's try this.

00:00:17.166 --> 00:00:19.958
Each of you described
the things you've written to the chip.

00:00:19.958 --> 00:00:22.083
I’ll compare them to the chip's memory.

00:00:22.083 --> 00:00:25.083
If it seems reasonable,
I'll give you partial credit.

00:00:30.500 --> 00:00:33.291
Annie: On Saturday,
I bought a bottle of orange juice

00:00:33.291 --> 00:00:36.291
from CVS before coming to school.

00:00:37.083 --> 00:00:39.541
I placed it on my desk

00:00:39.541 --> 00:00:41.916
and took out my computer

00:00:41.916 --> 00:00:44.375
and started
reviewing the Logisim simulation.

00:00:44.375 --> 00:00:45.833
The Noam sent me.

00:00:48.958 --> 00:00:50.166
Noam: we went to the eighth floor to,

00:00:50.166 --> 00:00:53.416
print our datasheets and stuff,

00:00:54.458 --> 00:00:56.541
but they were out of paper

00:00:56.541 --> 00:00:59.791
in the colored printer,
so we couldn't print it

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:03.000
there.

00:01:04.708 --> 00:01:05.750
Zeph: So here's the thing,

00:01:05.750 --> 00:01:09.958
I designed a box. So the breadboard can fit into the box.

00:01:10.166 --> 00:01:11.583
And our presentation looks very nice.

00:01:17.583 --> 00:01:19.708
Annie: On Sunday, I was

00:01:19.708 --> 00:01:23.166
figuring out this neuroimaging headset thing

00:01:23.583 --> 00:01:27.208
that is required for us to have interfaced
with our circuit,

00:01:28.291 --> 00:01:31.041
getting familiar
with its inputs and outputs

00:01:31.041 --> 00:01:34.416
so that we can gain access to the memory

00:01:34.416 --> 00:01:37.416
we wanted.

00:01:38.833 --> 00:01:40.416
Annie: So we went upstairs

00:01:40.416 --> 00:01:43.416
trying to print whatever document we have,

00:01:44.041 --> 00:01:47.125
but apparently
all of the printers are out of paper,

00:01:47.125 --> 00:01:51.375
so we had to go to this plotter room
where there's a single,

00:01:51.375 --> 00:01:54.375
large printer.

00:02:08.500 --> 00:02:10.583
Noam: I used the stripper
to make a lot of baby wires,

00:02:10.583 --> 00:02:13.333
because all of the chips
need to be connected to power and ground,

00:02:13.333 --> 00:02:16.333
so it makes it more efficient
for wiring later on.

00:02:19.208 --> 00:02:22.000
Zeph: I got LEDs, put it on a perf board,

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:25.708
and then I soldered it together
to make an LED matrix.

00:02:28.208 --> 00:02:29.000
Zeph: So uh Sunday was a

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:30.458
was a pretty chill day for me.

00:02:30.458 --> 00:02:35.083
I just, you know, unrolled my box
and then I sent it to the AACE Lab

00:02:35.125 --> 00:02:38.125
so they can laser cut.

00:02:43.625 --> 00:02:47.541
Annie: We needed a really good wire stripper
to speed up the process.

00:02:48.083 --> 00:02:51.708
But when I went and checked for it
in the drawer, it wasn't there.

00:02:52.458 --> 00:02:53.833
I was in so much stress.

00:02:53.833 --> 00:02:56.833
I literally shot off from the building.

00:02:57.041 --> 00:02:59.541
But remembered to close the drawer of course.

00:02:59.541 --> 00:03:02.875
And flew to this hardware store down two avenues.

00:03:18.250 --> 00:03:21.750
Noam: I needed a cardboard box
for the circuit components,

00:03:21.750 --> 00:03:25.375
so I went down to the basement
of the foundation building

00:03:25.375 --> 00:03:28.375
because I remember that
they had boxes there in the pipe room.

00:03:34.333 --> 00:03:38.541
Zeph: I had to get chips for our circuit,

00:03:38.541 --> 00:03:41.791
and then I had to download the datasheets
from TI.

00:03:42.291 --> 00:03:44.833
Fun fact,
they make all the chips in the world.

00:03:44.833 --> 00:03:46.500
It's crazy, I know.

00:03:46.500 --> 00:03:51.541
And then after I download the data
sheets, we were all ready to go.

00:03:54.958 --> 00:03:57.166
Okay, I've got everything written down.

00:03:57.166 --> 00:03:59.291
I will provide you with the
feedbacks later this week.

